<main class="about">
  <h1>About</h1>
  <p class="about-sub">Leonardo Baeta | senior embedded Linux / platform engineer | Santos, Brazil</p>

  <section class="about-sec">
    <h2>The short version</h2>
    <p>
      I've spent fifteen-plus years writing C and C++ for hardware that has to
      keep working: power-grid monitoring equipment, ECG monitors, X-ray
      inspection systems, industrial automation. These days I'm the sole
      firmware architect for a power-grid controller built from scratch -
      custom Yocto Linux image, networking, security standards, and field
      maintainability included.
    </p>
    <p>
      What pulls me is the layer most software never touches: code that talks
      to silicon, operating systems shaped into products, systems that have
      to answer on time, the machinery everything else stands on. Fifteen
      years in, and I still want to take it apart.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="about-sec">
    <h2>What this site is</h2>
    <p>
      In 2014 I bought a chest of hardware with big plans - a scope, radios,
      displays, sensors. Life had other ideas. Ten years later I finally have
      the skills, and the time, to open it. This site is me opening it in
      public.
    </p>
    <p>
      Most posts are <strong>field notes</strong>: me learning something in
      public, dead ends included. A few are <strong>references</strong> -
      consolidated pieces I stand behind once a topic has clicked. The label
      on each post tells you which kind you're reading.
    </p>
    <p>
      The site itself scratches the same itch: built from scratch in Node.js
      and Express, no framework, self-hosted on a small VPS.
    </p>
  </section>

